    "## Crossings\n",
    "\n",
    "To begin with, we might want to determine where different lines cross each other without a transit station.  To do so, we have to find all edge crossings, which can be achieved as follows."
   ],
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": false
   },
   "id": "6ece949acdeed790"
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": "<Figure size 3000x1200 with 15 Axes>",
      "image/png": ""
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "plt.figure(figsize=(30, 12))\n",
    "i = 0\n",
    "for name, graph in subways:\n",
    "    # Obtain a list of all crossings\n",
    "    crossing_list = gdMetriX.get_crossings(graph)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Draw the graph first\n",
    "    ax = plt.subplot(3, 5, i + 1)\n",
    "    ax.set_title(name)\n",
    "    pos = gdMetriX.get_node_positions(graph)\n",
    "    nx.draw_networkx_edges(graph, pos, ax=ax)\n",
    "    nx.draw_networkx_nodes(graph, pos, ax=ax, node_size=25)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Remove all crossing lines (we assume those to represent the same train track set)\n",
    "    crossing_list = list(filter(lambda x: type(x.pos) is gdMetriX.crossingDataTypes.CrossingPoint, crossing_list))\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Draw the crossings as red dots\n",
    "    x_values = [point.pos.x for point in crossing_list]\n",
    "    y_values = [point.pos.y for point in crossing_list]\n",
    "    ax.plot(x_values, y_values, 'ro', ms=12)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    i += 1\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ],

    "results = [\n",
    "    [\"Name\", \"n\", \"m\", \"Visual Symmetry\", \"Area\", \"Tight area\", \"Aspect ratio\", \"Height\", \"Width\", \"Center of mass\", \"Closest elements\", \"Closest points\", \"Concentration\", \"Gabriel ratio\", \"Homogeneity\", \"Horizontal balance\", \"Vertical Balance\"]\n",
    "]\n",
    "\n",
    "for name, g in subways:\n",
    "    graph_list = [name, g.order(), len(g.edges()), gdMetriX.visual_symmetry(g),\n",
    "                  gdMetriX.area(g), gdMetriX.area_tight(g), gdMetriX.aspect_ratio(g),\n",
    "                  gdMetriX.height(g), gdMetriX.width(g), gdMetriX.center_of_mass(g),\n",
    "                  gdMetriX.closest_pair_of_elements(g)[2], gdMetriX.closet_pair_of_points(g)[2], gdMetriX.concentration(g),\n",
    "                  gdMetriX.gabriel_ratio(g), gdMetriX.homogeneity(g), gdMetriX.horizontal_balance(g),\n",
    "                  gdMetriX.vertical_balance(g)]\n",
    "\n",
    "    results.append(graph_list)\n",
    "    \n",
    "df = pd.DataFrame(results)\n",
    "display(HTML(df.to_html()))"

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "source": [
    "We can see, that Moscow has the most symmetric subway layout (according to the visual symmetry value of 0.89252), while Hong Kong has the most irregular layout (with a visual symmetry value of just 0.556229) . The London underground covers by far the most area, which more than 15 times larger than the smallest subway, Barcelona - according to the size of the tight area, which calculates area using the convex hull."
   ],
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": false
   },
   "id": "35901b0719325098"
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "source": [
    "## Edge- and nodewise parameters\n",
    "\n",
    "Some properties are not global, but instead defined for each individual node, edge or crossing. We will illustrate how to analyse such local features. To do so, we are going to look at the distribution of edge lengths, which tells us how long the distance between stations is.\n",
    "\n",
    "We begin by drawing some violin plots for the edge length distribution."
   ],
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": false
   },
   "id": "5ec2ca17f5c5f694"
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": "<Figure size 1600x400 with 1 Axes>",
      "image/png": ""
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "data = []\n",
    "labels = []\n",
    "for name, g in subways:\n",
    "    pos = gdMetriX.get_node_positions(g)\n",
    "    edge_lengths = [gdMetriX.euclidean_distance(pos[edge[0]], pos[edge[1]]) for edge in g.edges()]\n",
    "    data.append(edge_lengths)\n",
    "    labels.append(name)\n",
    "\n",
    "data = sorted(data, key=lambda x: max(x), reverse=True)\n",
    "    \n",
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots()\n",
    "fig.set_figheight(4)\n",
    "fig.set_figwidth(16)\n",
    "ax.set_xticks(np.arange(1, len(labels) + 1), labels=labels)\n",
    "ax.violinplot(data)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ],
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": false,
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2024-05-04T12:53:51.655440900Z",
     "start_time": "2024-05-04T12:53:50.896483Z"
    }
   },
   "id": "6a25396f3b6c78ca"
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "source": [
    "We can see that the distance between stations vary hugely. Let us plot the average edge length on a heatmap to spot densely populated areas using the `heatmap` function."
   ],
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": false
   },
   "id": "5b792d3c59619b8a"
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": "<Figure size 2000x1000 with 15 Axes>",
      "image/png": ""
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "plt.figure(figsize=(20, 10))\n",
    "i = 0\n",
    "for name, g in subways:\n",
    "    ax = plt.subplot(3, 5, i + 1)\n",
    "    ax.set_title(name)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    pos = gdMetriX.get_node_positions(g)\n",
    "    edge_lengths = [gdMetriX.euclidean_distance(pos[edge[0]], pos[edge[1]]) for edge in g.edges()]\n",
    "    edge_pos = [gdMetriX.Vector.from_point(pos[edge[0]]).mid(gdMetriX.Vector.from_point(pos[edge[1]])) for edge in g.edges()]\n",
    "    \n",
    "    x_values = [x for x, y in pos.values()]\n",
    "    y_values = [y for x, y in pos.values()]\n",
    "    \n",
    "    heatmap = gdMetriX.heatmap(g, edge_pos, edge_lengths, 20)\n",
    "    ax.imshow(heatmap, cmap='viridis', interpolation='nearest')\n",
    "    \n",
    "    i+=1\n",
    "    \n",
    "plt.show()"
   ],
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": false,
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2024-05-04T12:53:55.935763Z",
     "start_time": "2024-05-04T12:53:51.632503200Z"

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "source": [
    "For some cities, the average edge length seems to increase as one goes further away from the centre, however, for the most part, the edge lengths seem to be roughly evenly distributed. Maybe stations are still close along each subway line, but the distance between lines increases. Maybe we can detect a pattern when looking at the node density instead.\n",
    "\n",
    "Instead of building the average of a value as for the edge length above, we simply want to count the number of vertices in each grid cell of the heatmap. To do so, we simply set `average=False` and supply `None` as the list of values."
   ],
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": false
   },
   "id": "dfb02480768868f6"
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": "<Figure size 2000x1000 with 15 Axes>",
      "image/png": ""
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "plt.figure(figsize=(20, 10))\n",
    "i = 0\n",
    "for name, g in subways:\n",
    "    ax = plt.subplot(3, 5, i + 1)\n",
    "    ax.set_title(name)\n",
    "\n",
    "    pos = [point for point in gdMetriX.get_node_positions(g).values()]\n",
    "    heatmap = gdMetriX.heatmap(g, pos, None, 20, average=False)\n",
    "    ax.imshow(heatmap, cmap='viridis', interpolation='nearest')\n",
    "    \n",
    "    i+=1\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ],
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": false,
